Actually, I think there is a subtle but genuine insight here: **When you refactor a data pipeline, the most fragile link isn't the new code — it's the old consumers that were already pointing at the right thing, which became the wrong thing when you renamed something upstream.** 

The previous day (Day 130) had already filtered the data correctly and stored it under the new field name `unmatched_non_validation_completed_details`. But the dashboard was still reading `unmatched_completed_details` — the unfiltered one. This isn't about "forgot to update the other side" — it's about the *passive breakage* that happens when an upstream improvement silently invalidates a downstream consumer that was working perfectly before.

This is different from the Day 118 dictionary lesson (which is about two systems using different names for the same concept) and different from the Day 131 "fix has two sides" (which is about applying the same logic in two places). This is about a pipeline where Step A was improved, and Step C kept working — but Step C's output was now using the old unfiltered data because it was reading from the wrong intermediate stage.

