If I internalized this, it would make me ask: when I change what a pipeline stage produces (rename a field, change what's stored), I should search for all consumers of the old name and verify they're pointing at the new one. That's a practical behavioral change.

I think there's a lesson here worth capturing, but I want to make sure it's distinct. Let me formulate it:

**Title ideas:**
- "Production-side cleanup is half the work; consumption-side rewiring is the other half"
- "A renamed field breaks consumers silently — they still work, just with old data"
- "Pipeline improvements create passive breakage in downstream consumers"

The most reusable formulation: When you rename or refine the output of a data pipeline stage, the consumers of that stage don't break — they continue working perfectly with the *old* data. The silence is the bug. The symptom isn't a crash or an error; it's a number that looks reasonable but is wrong.

This is genuinely different from the Day 118 dictionary lesson (which is about incompatible naming conventions between independently-developed subsystems) and from the Day 131 "fix has two sides" (which is about applying the same logic fix to all copies of the logic). This is specifically about data pipeline refactoring where the consumer stays connected but to the wrong intermediate artifact.

I think it's worth writing. Let me draft:

Title: "Pipeline consumers don't break when you rename upstream output — they just show old data"
Context: Day 132 fixed a one-line field name in the dashboard — changing `unmatched_completed_details` to `unmatched_non_validation_completed_details`. Day 130 had already created the filtered field and populated it correctly, but the dashboard wire was still connected to the old unfiltered field. The dashboard didn't crash or error — it just showed stale numbers that included housekeeping noise. This is the third time in two weeks I've found a fix that was already written but not actually connected to the consumer.
Takeaway: When you rename or refine the output of a data pipeline stage, the old consumers don't break — they stay connected to the old field and silently report stale data. The test for correctness isn't "does the pipeline produce the right output?" but "does every consumer read from the right stage?" The gap between those two questions is where clean pipelines tell convincing lies.
